  "url": "dimensions-and-units-1.html",
  "type": "Section",
  "number": "1.3",
  "title": "Dimensions and units",
  "body": " Dimensions and units   The Plan  Dimensions and units are critical to our ability to collect data, make valid quantitative and even qualitative comparisons, and draw conclusions.   Measurements have units (e.g., cm, pounds, liters)  We use identities to move between units and we use fundamental relations (e.g., geometry formulas) to move between dimensions.   Facts  To compare quantities we need a common unit, we convert to a common unit, or we give up.    Two sides of an equation must have identical units.    Two terms added together must have identical units.    Two terms multiplied\/divided are allowed to have different units.    To convert between units, multiply by identities (e.g., 1 yd = 3 ft) to cancel unwanted units and obtain desired units.   How many millimeters are in 1 foot?  How can we calculate areas from lengths?  How many square millimeters are in 1 square foot?  Which is bigger or ?    Volumes, areas, and other amounts  Instead of identities, use fundamental relations (e.g., geometry formulas) to convert between measurements with different dimensions.  A flat, circular colony of yeast has diameter of 1.2 mm. What is the area of the colony?    Keeping track of units on functions  When appropriate we want to make good use of the benefits of function notation and function manipulation, while preserving the unit of the underlying measurement. In particular, we want to be able to use given information to determine when we are evaluating a function (units of the input) or solving an equation (units of the output).  Consider two mathematical functions used to represent the change in these quantities, and .    What are dimensions and sensible units for each?    How can we combine these functions (measurements) to define other realistic measurements?      Take-away messages    Dimensional analysis – Always check to make sure dimensions match on each side of the equals sign!    Functions describe relations between measurements, so inputs and outputs have units and dimensions.    Only compose functions when their units and dimensions match.        Quick practice   Oklahoma’s State Champion Sparkleberry tree  read more here http:\/\/www.forestry.ok. gov\/champion-trees  has a diameter at breast height of inches, convert this to centimeters. Oklahoma’s State Champion Sparkleberry tree has a diameter at breast height of inches, as any good scientist should, we convert this to centimeters using .   Given the diameter found in Question (in centimeters), what is the area of the corresponding cross-sectional slice of tree? Given the diameter found in Question (in centimeters) we need to find the radius before computing the area. The radius is half of the diameter, , so the area of the corresponding cross-sectional slice of tree is    "
