  "title": "Linear functions and their graphs",
  "body": " Linear functions and their graphs   The Plan  Linear functions are the basis for most relationships that we can think about.    linear function  A relationship defined by    , with constants and , or     , with constant and a point   is called a linear function between the variables  and . If the formula involves only adding and subtracting constants with variables multiplied by constants, the equation describes a linear function.    The slope of a linear function passing through two points and is defined as the ratio of the change in output over the change in input ( rise over run ),   Notation  In general, in biological applications we rarely have inputs\/outputs called and – for example we have mass and volume. These labels, while different from what we are used to are meant to make problems more meaningful!     Here we will derive a common (and commonly mis-remembered) temperature formula.   Recall: What is the formula for computing the temperature in F if you know temperature in C?   Data: Consider the following data:       C  F    0  32    20  68    37  98.6    100  212      Graph it: Plot the points to determine whether a linear function holds.   Slope: Identify a pair of points and compute the slope.   Linear functions: Now write , first in point-slope form, then simplify to slope-intercept form.     Sample pgfplots plot   A pgfplots example, with a function, a parametric curve, and some points plotted.       Notice that the definition gives us all we need to derive both point-slope form and slope-intercept form. Let our point be and instead of , choose to be any other point on the line.    Once again rewrite this as slope-intercept form.   How are point-slope and slope-intercept forms related?     Which of the following are linear functions?                  Interpolation  Frequently we use linear functions to interpolate or predict values occurring between two known values. This technique is called linear interpolation, and is illustrated in the following example.     Here we look at the onset of AIDS symptoms in the years after initial HIV infection. Four years after infection 17% had symptoms, and seven years after infection 33% had symptoms.   Write the formula for a linear function that relates the percent of patients with AIDS symptoms to time (years measured since infection).    Define and interpret the slope and intercept (units included).    How many patients (what percent) have symptoms after five and a half years?    Using this model, at what time would you predict that half of all exposed patients have AIDS symptoms? What must you do to answer this question?       Important facts about linear functions  The following work should help us reason through linear functions (and eventually many more).    Example    Behavior    Slope     A proportional relation is a linear relation in which the output is proportional to input. In general     A fundamental relation , links mass measured in and volume measured in .    Is this fundamental relation a proportional relation?    What are the units on each term?    What is the mass of an object with volume ?    Is the formula for temperature conversion a proportional relation?    What is constant?    the ratio of output over input proportional relation:    the ratio of change in output over change in input linear function: (i.e., slope is constant)      Quick practice   In Question of the previous section, we talked about the relationship between area and radius. Is that relationship linear? Why or why not? In Question of the previous section, we talked about the relationship between area and radius, . This is not linear, since we must square the radius to get the area.   In Question of the previous section, we talked about the relationship between radius and diameter. Is that relationship linear? Why or why not? In Question of the previous section, we talked about the relationship between radius and diameter. This is linear since , in fact this is proportional since the radius is a constant multiple of the diameter. This is a good reminder that dividing by two is the same as multiplying by one half.   (This one might not be so quick practice.) In chemistry we use the Lineweaver-Burk or double-reciprocal plot to determine properties of a chemical reaction. We graph a surprisingly complicated looking, but still linear, relationship where is the reaction rate or velocity , is the substrate concentration, and and are parameters in the relationship between our original variables and . Solve for (not the reciprocal of ) as a function of . In solving for (steps not shown), we should eventually come upon the formula . This an example of a type of function we will study in more detail later this semester.   Roughly speaking, the phrase is proportional to means what? Roughly speaking, the phrase is proportional to means is a multiple of .   "
