  "number": "2.6",
  "title": "Second derivatives and applications",
  "body": " Second derivatives and applications   The Plan  Given our work on the mechanics of computing derivatives, we will focus on the interpretation and application of derivatives.    Derivatives  When discussing functions and derivatives, the derivative of a function refers to its first derivative. Since derivatives of functions are functions too, we can take higher derivatives using our current methods. Perhaps the most common higher derivative is the second derivative.   Interpretation  As we have seen (and will see), the    describes the    describes the    Compute for the following functions                Concavity describes the shape of a graph.    a graph of is concave up if it bends upward,     if its first derivative is increasing, or    if (the second derivative is positive)      a graph of is concave down if it bends downward,     if its first derivative is decreasing, or    if (the second derivative is negative)        A hint about quadratics  Consider the quadratic function .    A help when sketching  The second derivative helps us add more detail to the sketch of a function.          function    derivative    second derivative      A famous example from physics  We often use rates of change to describe movement of an object.      Name  Interpretation  Notation                         Consider a seed in a flower in a very tall tree. The seed pops straight into the air with an initial velocity of 9.8 meters per second from an initial height of 14.7 meters. The position (height in meters from ground level) is described by find the velocity of the seed and its acceleration.  Continuing based on our work above,    At what time does the seed reach its greatest height?    What is the greatest height?    How long until the seed lands?      Critical points and second derivatives  For a function , a critical point is an -value at which the derivative is zero or not defined. Here we focus on the kind of critical point where .At such a point the function commonly experiences a change in behavior.     image     image     Derivatives and important points  Derivatives encode important information about functions.    critical points (where ) often indicate where a function changes behavior    inflection points (possible where ) indicate where a function changes shape (concavity)      Facts about derivatives   Recall the following facts about first and second derivatives.  Derivatives describe .      First derivative  Function             Second derivatives describe .      Second derivative  Function             A graph of can have local optima optima is an alternate word for extrema, indicating optimum or extreme values that a function takes on. In general, an individual optimum value is called a local maximum or minimum. at a critical point if or is undefined. If the function has an optimum value, it is    a local maximum if the derivative switches from    a local minimum if the derivative switches from     There is no local optimum value if the derivative does not change sign.   The Second Derivative Test outlined below helps is find local optima at critical points :    If , then a local maximum value of occurs at and the function value is    If , then a local minimum value of occurs at and the function value is    If , then we have to look more closely at the sign of the first derivative     We have to know the locations of the critical points (from the first derivative) in order to apply the SDT!   Consider the functions and , their first and second derivatives, and their graphs. Find local optima for each function.  Mathematical functions of the form are important in statistics and modeling (fisheries models, for example). The graph is pictured below:    image   From the graph, describe the behavior and concavity.  Is there a maximum value that the function takes on? If so, where does this happen?  Mathematical functions of the form are used to model the growth rate of populations that can be described by logistic growth. Here the growth rate of the population is a function of the current size of the population. Find the local maximum growth rate of the population. At which size does it grow the fastest?  Consider , find critical points and use the SDT to find local optima (maxima and\/or minima). Using information about increasing, decreasing, concavity, and the locations of local extrema sketch the graph .  A global optimum value is guaranteed to exist for a function on an interval. The global maximum is the largest value that the function achieves, the global minimum is the smallest value that the function achieves. Global extrema occur at critical points or endpoints of the interval.   The steps are as follows:    Evaluate function at endpoints.    Find all critical points.    Compute the function value at critical points.    Largest is the global maximum, smallest is the global minimum.    Find global optima of the function on the interval  .    Biological and scientific applications  In general, we might want to optimize production of a chemical, yield or harvest of a plant or animal product, reproductive output, survival, growth rate. Statistics also relies heavily on the derivative and maximization to find best values of a statistical parameter from data.      Quick practice   Is concave up or concave down at ? The function has derivatives and . Notice that so is concave up everywhere, including at ?    Does have a local minimum or maximum at its critical point?  The critical point of is and the second derivative of is . Since (as we just saw in the previous Question), is concave up at the critical point which means the point is a local minimum.    What is the name of the third derivative of position? (I have not told you this, but it should not be too hard to find.)  Jerk. Hey, watch your attitude.    "
